It seems that I made an incorrect assumption about how to structure the schema and XML file.

Let's try a different approach. Since we're generating an XML file based on a GeoJSON file, we can create a separate Java class that generates the XML file programmatically.

Here's an example of how you could generate the XML file:
```java
import org.json.JSONObject;
import org.json.JsonParser;

public class MissionPlanGenerator {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        // Load GeoJSON file
        String geoJsonFile = "path/to/geojson/file.geojson";
        JSONObject geoJsonData = new JSONObject(new JsonParser().parse(geoJsonFile));

        // Generate XML file
        generateXml(geoJsonData);
    }

    public static void generateXml(JSONObject geoJsonData) throws Exception {
        // Create XML output stream
        java.io.OutputStream outputStream = System.out;
        java.io.PrintWriter writer = new PrintWriter(outputStream);

        // Write XML header
        writer.println("<?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?>");

        // Write root element
        writer.println("<MissionPlan>");

        // Add CompositeTaskInformation element
        writer.println("  <CompositeTaskInformation>");

        // Add task elements
        for (int i = 0; i < geoJsonData.getJSONArray("features").length(); i++) {
            JSONObject feature = geoJsonData.getJSONArray("features").getJSONObject(i);
            writer.println("    <Task>");
            writer.println("      <Name>" + feature.getString("properties.name") + "</Name>");
            writer.println("      <Description>" + feature.getString("properties.description") + "</Description>");
            writer.println("    </Task>");
        }

        // Close CompositeTaskInformation element
        writer.println("  </CompositeTaskInformation>");

        // Close root element
        writer.println("</MissionPlan>");

        // Flush output stream
        writer.flush();
    }
}
```
This Java class loads a GeoJSON file, parses its contents, and generates an XML file based on the data. The resulting XML file can be written to a file or printed to the console.

Please note that this is just an example code snippet and may need to be modified to fit your specific use case.